# Verify the wake loop end to end against a live worker

## Step

Drive the real loop the way a supervising Claude session will: spawn a pi worker in a herdr pane, run `herdr-ping-wait` via Bash `run_in_background`, send the worker a prompt, and confirm the orchestrator wakes exactly once when the turn ends — then again for a second turn, with no duplicate or stale fires (the two failure modes shepherd has today). Exercise the error path (kill the provider request or force a stream error) and confirm `turn_error` wakes the waiter. Confirm the shepherd fallback boundary: pane death (`pane_gone`) is still shepherd's job — document the split.

Compare against `herdr agent wait --status idle` on the same run to record why the ping loop wins (or where it doesn't).

HITL because Joel should watch at least one live run and sign off on the feel of the loop before the skill doc changes.

Resolution: a receipt of the live run (commands + observed events) posted here, plus any contract or code fixes fed back to the build tickets.

## Resolution (2026-07-12) — live run receipt, all tests passed, no code changes needed

Run by the steering session (`wF:p1`) with Joel live; fresh worker pane `wF:p4` (`wf-verify`) so the extension was loaded at pi startup.

1. **Turn end wakes once.** Armed `herdr-ping-wait wF:p4 --timeout 180` via `run_in_background`, then `herdr pane run wF:p4 'pi "<one-sentence prompt>"'`. Waiter exited 0 printing `{"event":"turn_ended","pane_id":"wF:p4",...,"turn_index":0,"last_message_tail":"I'm alive."}`.
2. **No stale re-fire.** Immediate re-run `herdr-ping-wait wF:p4 --timeout 5` → exit 2, nothing delivered. This is the shepherd bug, absent.
3. **Second turn, with tool use, still one event.** Re-armed the waiter, sent a follow-up forcing a shell tool call (`herdr agent send` + `send-keys enter`). Waiter delivered `turn_index:1` with the tool output in the tail. Spool holds exactly 2 lines for 2 exchanges — the tool-call turn produced no extra event, confirming `agent_settled` (not `turn_end`) was the right emission point.
4. **Error path.** Startup auth failure (`pi --provider openai` with no key) never reaches the agent loop → no spool event, as the research predicted; that failure class stays with shepherd/`pane_gone`. A **mid-loop** failure (`OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-invalid... pi --provider openai --model gpt-4o-mini -p hi`) produced exactly one `turn_error` line carrying the full 401 message in `error`.
5. **EOF-init observed in the wild:** the `wV:err` spool line was written before any watcher had ever seen that spool; a fresh wait starts at EOF and correctly does not replay it.

Comparison receipt vs `herdr agent wait`: earlier this same session, herdr's coarse status reported both build workers `idle · startup` while they were visibly mid-task — the heuristic status the old loop depends on. The ping loop keys on pi's own settle event instead and carries turn semantics + message tail, which `agent wait` cannot.

Boundary confirmed: extension owns "turn settled / turn errored"; shepherd (or `pane_gone` watching) owns process death and non-pi panes.
